WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.600
Okay, our next speaker probably doesn't need an introduction, but I was told I'm supposed

00:00:09.600 --> 00:00:12.500
to introduce people, so I'm going to do it.

00:00:12.500 --> 00:00:13.500
It's Joe Cheng.

00:00:13.500 --> 00:00:19.100
He is the CTO of our studio, and he is the original creator of Shiny.

00:00:19.100 --> 00:00:24.100
Today he's going to be talking about Styling Shiny apps with Sass and Bootstrap 4.

00:00:24.100 --> 00:00:27.100
Thanks, Winston.

00:00:27.100 --> 00:00:38.500
Yeah, today we're going to talk about Styling Shiny apps, and I'm going to start by talking

00:00:38.500 --> 00:00:43.700
about the current state of the world when it comes to Styling Shiny.

00:00:43.700 --> 00:00:48.240
So here are just some of the approaches that I personally have seen people using.

00:00:48.240 --> 00:00:52.320
The first and probably most common approach to Styling Shiny apps is to not do it.

00:00:52.320 --> 00:00:54.080
Just accept the defaults.

00:00:54.080 --> 00:00:58.639
And honestly, how many of us are just happy it works at all?

00:00:58.639 --> 00:00:59.639
Yeah.

00:00:59.639 --> 00:01:05.080
So this is probably the simplest possible example of a Shiny app, but even that, you

00:01:05.080 --> 00:01:06.279
know, it's something presentable.

00:01:06.279 --> 00:01:08.800
You can show it to your coworkers.

00:01:08.800 --> 00:01:14.279
And certainly as of 2012, when Shiny was new, this was pretty exciting and modern-looking.

00:01:14.279 --> 00:01:15.800
Less so in 2020.

00:01:15.800 --> 00:01:17.919
And you can take that lack of styling pretty far.

00:01:17.919 --> 00:01:24.760
I mean, this is an app called Radiant by Vincent Nyes, and it is using only the default style,

00:01:24.760 --> 00:01:27.680
and he's able to do quite a lot with this app.

00:01:27.680 --> 00:01:29.599
Today I'm going to focus on this example app.

00:01:29.599 --> 00:01:33.160
This is an evolution of an app that I used for a talk last year.

00:01:33.160 --> 00:01:37.879
I'm not going to get into the functionality, but I've made it look a little bit different

00:01:37.879 --> 00:01:41.480
than a regular Shiny app or the most common kinds of Shiny app in terms of structure,

00:01:41.480 --> 00:01:43.040
but the styling is still the same.

00:01:43.040 --> 00:01:44.040
This is the default style.

00:01:44.279 --> 00:01:47.279
I haven't changed any of the fonts or colors or anything like that.

00:01:47.279 --> 00:01:53.239
So Shiny's default UI is powered by Bootstrap, which is not a piece of software that we created.

00:01:53.239 --> 00:01:56.080
It was created originally at Twitter and is now independent.

00:01:56.080 --> 00:02:00.199
And this is one of the most popular pieces of software in the world today.

00:02:00.199 --> 00:02:05.519
It is the number six most popular GitHub project by stars across all of GitHub.

00:02:05.519 --> 00:02:11.240
And it was designed to be easily customized, but easily customized by web designers.

00:02:11.240 --> 00:02:15.119
They weren't thinking of our users, unfortunately.

00:02:15.119 --> 00:02:17.559
And this is an example of what Bootstrap looks like.

00:02:17.559 --> 00:02:22.160
This is an example from Bootstrap's documentation of just a simple page.

00:02:22.160 --> 00:02:27.800
And there are a lot of things about this page that, I mean, it looks nice, maybe a little

00:02:27.800 --> 00:02:32.960
bit generic, but this is that same page with the one change of Bootstrap being removed.

00:02:32.960 --> 00:02:33.960
It looks like this.

00:02:33.960 --> 00:02:39.199
So you can see that the amount of work that Bootstrap is doing for us is substantial.

00:02:39.199 --> 00:02:41.240
It's taking care of typography.

00:02:41.240 --> 00:02:42.240
It's doing layout.

00:02:42.240 --> 00:02:45.839
There are buttons and nav bars and search.

00:02:45.839 --> 00:02:51.639
All of that are components that come with Bootstrap, along with these different colors.

00:02:51.639 --> 00:02:54.960
So that's that first approach is just accepting the defaults.

00:02:54.960 --> 00:03:00.039
And I'm sure many people here how many people here are developing Shiny apps or have developed

00:03:00.039 --> 00:03:01.039
a Shiny app?

00:03:01.039 --> 00:03:02.039
Okay.

00:03:02.039 --> 00:03:03.039
Quite a few of you.

00:03:03.039 --> 00:03:05.960
And how many of you have just accepted the defaults and shipped apps?

00:03:05.960 --> 00:03:06.960
Okay.

00:03:07.720 --> 00:03:11.520
So the second approach is maybe you're not happy with the complete default look.

00:03:11.520 --> 00:03:14.320
You just want to punch it up a little bit, you know?

00:03:14.320 --> 00:03:19.639
And one way to do that is to use a prefabricated theme, such as the ones that come with Shiny

00:03:19.639 --> 00:03:22.320
themes, the Shiny themes package.

00:03:22.320 --> 00:03:26.759
So this, again, is that generic example with Cranwells.

00:03:26.759 --> 00:03:30.960
And with a single argument to FluidPage, you can apply a different theme.

00:03:30.960 --> 00:03:36.399
And you can see the colors change, the fonts changed, the spacing has changed very slightly,

00:03:36.399 --> 00:03:37.679
theme capitalization.

00:03:37.679 --> 00:03:41.320
And all of that is accomplished by just that one argument.

00:03:41.320 --> 00:03:46.360
And there are a few, maybe one or two dozen different themes that are available.

00:03:46.360 --> 00:03:48.080
And there's some variety there.

00:03:48.080 --> 00:03:51.199
But you're making sort of an all or nothing choice.

00:03:51.199 --> 00:03:53.880
So if you like one of these, great.

00:03:53.880 --> 00:03:56.520
But you're going to take the entire style that that offers you.

00:03:56.520 --> 00:04:01.399
And there's not really a lot of handholding it does to customize it on top of that.

00:04:01.399 --> 00:04:07.559
So this is that second approach, is you want it just to look a little bit different.

00:04:07.559 --> 00:04:09.279
You might also want it to look a lot different.

00:04:09.279 --> 00:04:11.039
And a lot of people, I think, are doing that these days.

00:04:11.039 --> 00:04:15.080
How many people here are using something like Shiny Dashboard, Shiny Material, a different

00:04:15.080 --> 00:04:16.079
Oh, my gosh.

00:04:16.079 --> 00:04:17.079
OK.

00:04:17.079 --> 00:04:18.079
So quite a lot of you.

00:04:18.079 --> 00:04:22.079
And I think this took us a little bit by surprise, because we had created Shiny Dashboard at

00:04:22.079 --> 00:04:25.320
our studio in order to actually create dashboards.

00:04:25.320 --> 00:04:29.040
And then to see what people are using it for, which is almost everything that people build

00:04:29.320 --> 00:04:30.799
with Shiny apps, has been surprising.

00:04:30.799 --> 00:04:34.399
But I think it was because people just want a different look than the default.

00:04:34.399 --> 00:04:35.959
I'm seeing a lot of nods.

00:04:35.959 --> 00:04:36.959
OK.

00:04:36.959 --> 00:04:38.519
So this is Shiny Dashboard.

00:04:38.519 --> 00:04:45.839
This is Shiny Material by Eric Ray Anderson that makes things look more googly, I guess.

00:04:45.839 --> 00:04:51.519
And then this is from the R Interface project, an Argon-based UI toolkit.

00:04:51.519 --> 00:04:53.040
And Shiny was always designed to do this.

00:04:53.040 --> 00:04:57.480
It was always designed to let people use things besides our defaults.

00:04:57.600 --> 00:04:59.359
So that's a great option.

00:04:59.359 --> 00:05:04.399
But what it doesn't do, necessarily, is provide this capability, which is you want specific

00:05:04.399 --> 00:05:06.880
fonts, colors, and styles.

00:05:06.880 --> 00:05:09.119
I'm going to come back to this in a moment.

00:05:09.119 --> 00:05:14.920
But I think we all who have tried to do this can agree, shouldn't this be easier than it

00:05:14.920 --> 00:05:16.760
is today with Shiny?

00:05:16.760 --> 00:05:20.399
Definitely requires a lot of custom CSS.

00:05:20.399 --> 00:05:24.559
And before I start talking about that, I just want to give a nod to this last approach,

00:05:24.559 --> 00:05:25.559
which is native HTML.

00:05:25.640 --> 00:05:27.640
I'm not going to talk much about this today.

00:05:27.640 --> 00:05:34.119
But you do always have the option to forego most of Shiny's UI layout CSS style and do

00:05:34.119 --> 00:05:37.799
your own thing or work with a web designer who can do this for you.

00:05:37.799 --> 00:05:43.440
Let R do what R is good at and let HTML and CSS designers do what they're good at.

00:05:43.440 --> 00:05:47.839
This is an example of an app I wrote a few years ago that this is all powered by Shiny.

00:05:47.839 --> 00:05:51.679
All of those numbers, the plots, are outputs that are driven by Shiny.

00:05:51.679 --> 00:05:55.339
But the entire front end is constructed using HTML and CSS.

00:05:55.339 --> 00:05:56.339
So that is a possibility.

00:05:56.339 --> 00:05:58.820
But that's not what I want to focus on today.

00:05:58.820 --> 00:06:01.660
The thing I want to focus on today is this, right?

00:06:01.660 --> 00:06:05.660
Why is that funny?

00:06:05.660 --> 00:06:10.859
How can I get my Shiny app to match the official fonts and colors of my company?

00:06:10.859 --> 00:06:11.899
I get this question a lot.

00:06:11.899 --> 00:06:14.339
I get it from our customer success people.

00:06:14.339 --> 00:06:16.339
I get it from people at conferences.

00:06:16.339 --> 00:06:17.920
And maybe for you, it's not your company.

00:06:17.920 --> 00:06:19.500
Maybe it's your client.

00:06:19.500 --> 00:06:21.119
Maybe it's your university.

00:06:21.119 --> 00:06:22.119
Or whatever it is.

00:06:22.119 --> 00:06:27.320
But have some reason to prefer a specific set of fonts and colors.

00:06:27.320 --> 00:06:30.320
And this seems like it's something that should be pretty easy.

00:06:30.320 --> 00:06:32.480
And it turns out that it's not.

00:06:32.480 --> 00:06:41.040
And this, I hope, will be the most painful demo that you'll see here at RStudioConf.

00:06:41.040 --> 00:06:42.920
Here again is my app.

00:06:42.920 --> 00:06:54.760
And our designer, Greg, sent me this color and font branding guide for RStudio.

00:06:54.760 --> 00:06:58.399
And I want to take this Cranwheels app and make it look less generic and more RStudioish.

00:06:58.399 --> 00:07:02.600
So the first thing I want to do is I want to take this bright blue and change this to

00:07:02.600 --> 00:07:07.839
this accent orange, which has a hex color of whatever it is.

00:07:07.839 --> 00:07:13.359
So I'm going to do this the way you would do this today, by writing more CSS.

00:07:13.359 --> 00:07:17.119
I've already created the CSS file.

00:07:17.119 --> 00:07:25.640
And if you have some experience with web stuff, you've done this before, you use the inspector

00:07:25.640 --> 00:07:29.040
to figure out what kind of a selector you might want to write.

00:07:29.040 --> 00:07:36.440
And because I did this for many years, I can tell you that that is the right incantation

00:07:36.440 --> 00:07:39.480
for this.

00:07:39.480 --> 00:07:41.559
Everybody following along with that?

00:07:41.559 --> 00:07:43.239
Okay, great.

00:07:43.239 --> 00:07:45.799
So that color changed.

00:07:45.799 --> 00:07:47.679
It took me a lot longer than that to do it the first time.

00:07:47.679 --> 00:07:51.920
But sure enough, that works.

00:07:51.920 --> 00:07:55.600
But these links, let's update those links as well, right?

00:07:55.600 --> 00:08:00.320
So I'll say those are navs that are not active.

00:08:00.320 --> 00:08:03.440
And instead of changing the foreground color, I mean, the background color, I'm now going

00:08:03.440 --> 00:08:07.040
to change the foreground color.

00:08:07.040 --> 00:08:08.839
Okay.

00:08:08.839 --> 00:08:12.119
Now, you might think you're done.

00:08:12.119 --> 00:08:14.480
But actually, there are a few things missing.

00:08:14.480 --> 00:08:19.179
If I scroll down, there's a link here at the bottom that's still blue.

00:08:19.179 --> 00:08:21.440
If I hover over these...

00:08:21.440 --> 00:08:22.440
Oh.

00:08:22.440 --> 00:08:27.079
When I hover over these links, they're supposed to turn a slightly darker shade, and it doesn't

00:08:27.079 --> 00:08:28.079
do that.

00:08:28.079 --> 00:08:29.079
And if I click on...

00:08:29.079 --> 00:08:32.880
I don't know if you can see it with the projector, but when I click on a control, a focus ring

00:08:32.880 --> 00:08:35.640
is drawn, and that also is this blue color.

00:08:35.640 --> 00:08:38.479
And I want to replace all of those with orange.

00:08:38.479 --> 00:08:42.380
And the point is, I'm just trying to replace one color here.

00:08:42.380 --> 00:08:46.679
And I'm already falling into this rabbit hole of having to hunt down one little edge case

00:08:46.679 --> 00:08:49.760
after another and write CSS to overwrite it all.

00:08:49.760 --> 00:08:59.080
So this is not a great status quo that we're living in today.

00:08:59.080 --> 00:09:00.840
So why is this so difficult?

00:09:00.840 --> 00:09:06.479
Why does it take so much effort to just override one color?

00:09:06.479 --> 00:09:08.280
This is bootstrap CSS.

00:09:08.280 --> 00:09:09.479
I don't know if you guys in the back can...

00:09:09.479 --> 00:09:11.119
You know what?

00:09:11.119 --> 00:09:12.119
Just...

00:09:12.119 --> 00:09:14.400
There's a color that's being highlighted.

00:09:14.400 --> 00:09:15.440
There's a hex code.

00:09:15.440 --> 00:09:19.059
And this is the source code for bootstrap CSS.

00:09:19.059 --> 00:09:21.400
So this is saying that this link should be blue.

00:09:21.400 --> 00:09:24.960
That very specific shade of blue.

00:09:24.960 --> 00:09:30.440
This color appears all throughout the CSS file 25 different times.

00:09:30.440 --> 00:09:32.580
And some of them are pretty complicated.

00:09:32.580 --> 00:09:38.080
So if you as a Shiny app author want to change all of those instances of blue to that specific

00:09:38.080 --> 00:09:42.440
shade of orange, you would actually have to overwrite each one of those rules with custom

00:09:42.440 --> 00:09:43.440
CSS.

00:09:43.440 --> 00:09:47.919
And those are pretty complicated selectors that we're looking at here.

00:09:47.919 --> 00:09:53.119
So clearly this is not really a tenable strategy for changing colors.

00:09:53.119 --> 00:09:59.880
And in fact, imagine if you're not a Shiny app author, but instead you are the people

00:09:59.880 --> 00:10:00.880
maintaining bootstrap.

00:10:00.880 --> 00:10:04.599
I just gave away the punchline.

00:10:04.599 --> 00:10:09.760
If you are the developer of bootstrap, I mean, how much more painful is it for you as you're

00:10:09.760 --> 00:10:11.520
working on this framework?

00:10:11.520 --> 00:10:13.960
And it turns out that that is not what people do.

00:10:13.960 --> 00:10:16.919
People do not do search and replace 25 times to change colors.

00:10:16.919 --> 00:10:22.760
Instead, professional web developers use a language called Sass instead of CSS.

00:10:22.760 --> 00:10:26.760
Sass is CSS plus superpowers.

00:10:26.760 --> 00:10:27.760
I mean...

00:10:27.760 --> 00:10:28.760
I guess it's superpowers.

00:10:29.760 --> 00:10:33.440
But they're going to help us a lot today.

00:10:33.440 --> 00:10:39.520
Here you can see on the left, we've got Sass, which is CSS plus additional features.

00:10:39.520 --> 00:10:44.520
And the feature that we care about for today's purposes is Sass has the ability for you to

00:10:44.520 --> 00:10:46.960
declare and use variables.

00:10:46.960 --> 00:10:52.200
So instead of hard coding this color throughout the CSS, you write Sass code that declares

00:10:52.200 --> 00:10:56.320
a variable called primary, assigns it that color blue, and then everywhere in your Sass

00:10:56.880 --> 00:11:01.440
code, you use that variable instead of the hard-coded color.

00:11:01.440 --> 00:11:03.440
Now browsers don't understand Sass.

00:11:03.440 --> 00:11:10.159
So you have to run that Sass source through a Sass compiler, and you result in this style.css

00:11:10.159 --> 00:11:12.440
that replaces the variable with its value.

00:11:12.440 --> 00:11:14.080
You get the picture.

00:11:14.080 --> 00:11:18.000
And really, this Sass compiler is where we lose our users most of the time.

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:21.799
Because we are now talking about a tool chain that they are not familiar with and not really

00:11:21.799 --> 00:11:22.919
interested in using.

00:11:22.919 --> 00:11:28.159
But the point I want to get across is that Bootstrap was designed from the beginning

00:11:28.159 --> 00:11:31.239
for you to replace this color.

00:11:31.239 --> 00:11:36.919
They centralized in their Sass code that blue color into one variable.

00:11:36.919 --> 00:11:41.039
And then that variable is used throughout their Sass source.

00:11:41.039 --> 00:11:46.119
The upshot of this is that as our users, if we could set those Bootstrap variables, if

00:11:46.119 --> 00:11:50.760
we could override the values of those variables from R, then we could bend Bootstrap to our

00:11:50.760 --> 00:11:51.760
will.

00:11:51.880 --> 00:11:55.119
I want primary to be orange, and we would be done.

00:11:55.119 --> 00:11:59.039
So to that end, we've developed two new R packages that I'm talking about today.

00:11:59.039 --> 00:12:04.159
Well, I'm not going to talk about Sass, but Sass is the foundation that Bootstrap lib

00:12:04.159 --> 00:12:05.159
is built on.

00:12:05.159 --> 00:12:10.640
Sass is a way to compile Sass to CSS directly from R, but we've built these higher-level

00:12:10.640 --> 00:12:13.880
tools specifically for Bootstrap in Bootstrap lib.

00:12:13.880 --> 00:12:18.599
So you're not going to need to interact with Sass in order to use Bootstrap lib.

00:12:18.599 --> 00:12:23.200
In the rest of my talk, I'm mostly going to be focusing on Bootstrap lib.

00:12:23.200 --> 00:12:26.080
Bootstrap lib, you can think of it as R bindings for Bootstrap.

00:12:26.080 --> 00:12:29.239
It's designed to be used not only for Shiny, even though we're just going to be talking

00:12:29.239 --> 00:12:32.960
about Shiny today, but you can also use it with R Markdown, with HTML widgets, anywhere

00:12:32.960 --> 00:12:35.880
else in R where you might want to use Bootstrap.

00:12:35.880 --> 00:12:42.039
You can customize and re-customize Bootstrap straight from within R, and it also basically

00:12:42.039 --> 00:12:45.479
bundles in what used to be the separate package of Shiny themes.

00:12:45.479 --> 00:12:49.520
This is functionality that's included in Bootstrap lib, and I'm very excited to show

00:12:49.520 --> 00:12:50.520
you this.

00:12:50.520 --> 00:12:52.479
So this is how you use it.

00:12:52.479 --> 00:12:55.200
This is a typical Shiny app.

00:12:55.200 --> 00:12:58.520
First, you load the library.

00:12:58.520 --> 00:13:04.039
Second, you call bstheme new, and this declares that you are starting a new theme.

00:13:04.039 --> 00:13:08.359
It's kind of equivalent to calling plot.new.

00:13:08.359 --> 00:13:12.760
Step three, you set whatever customizations you'd like.

00:13:12.760 --> 00:13:17.400
In this case, I'm setting the body background color to pink and that primary link color

00:13:17.400 --> 00:13:18.400
to maroon.

00:13:18.400 --> 00:13:23.640
And then finally, you call the function called Bootstrap to build a custom build of Bootstrap

00:13:23.640 --> 00:13:29.599
that obeys those variables and inserts it into whatever UI you're calling it from.

00:13:29.599 --> 00:13:33.200
So in this case, this fluid page is going to have a Bootstrap dependency custom built

00:13:33.200 --> 00:13:39.320
for it and injected.

00:13:39.320 --> 00:13:43.440
So let's take a quick look at that.

00:13:43.440 --> 00:13:46.640
So I'm going to take this Cranwhales app again, and I've already done three of those steps.

00:13:46.640 --> 00:13:50.039
So library Bootstrap lib is here.

00:13:50.039 --> 00:13:56.039
I'm calling bstheme new, and I'm calling Bootstrap Bootstrap.

00:13:56.039 --> 00:13:59.640
So now all I need to do is add a variable.

00:13:59.640 --> 00:14:03.520
So the first thing we're going to do is we're going to change that primary color to that

00:14:03.520 --> 00:14:06.719
orange, and let's run the app.

00:14:06.719 --> 00:14:11.799
And sure enough, with that one change, the links are orange.

00:14:11.799 --> 00:14:12.880
This is orange.

00:14:12.880 --> 00:14:14.520
The link at the bottom is orange.

00:14:14.520 --> 00:14:20.440
If I click on this selector or this text input, the ring around it is orange.

00:14:20.440 --> 00:14:24.640
So everywhere in those 25 instances of blue, those are now orange.

00:14:24.640 --> 00:14:31.119
But let's go a step further, and let's take this gray background and change that to our

00:14:31.119 --> 00:14:33.119
studio dark blue.

00:14:33.159 --> 00:14:37.159
So that is called secondary.

00:14:45.159 --> 00:14:48.159
Oh, increase the font size?

00:14:48.159 --> 00:14:52.159
I didn't know if that voice was coming from inside my head.

00:14:52.159 --> 00:14:55.159
It's so faint.

00:14:55.159 --> 00:14:56.159
Yes, mother?

00:14:56.159 --> 00:14:57.159
All right.

00:14:57.159 --> 00:14:58.159
Sorry.

00:14:58.200 --> 00:15:03.200
Here, let me make that bigger.

00:15:03.200 --> 00:15:04.200
Yes.

00:15:04.200 --> 00:15:08.200
So bs, theme, add variables, primary, and secondary.

00:15:08.200 --> 00:15:11.200
And that's all we need to do.

00:15:11.200 --> 00:15:16.200
Which, let's be honest, isn't that kind of what you expect from Shiny in the first place?

00:15:16.200 --> 00:15:19.200
Shouldn't it always have been just, like, two variables?

00:15:19.239 --> 00:15:24.239
Okay.

00:15:24.239 --> 00:15:29.239
Which, if you're a skeptic, you might have been rolling your eyes a little bit that I

00:15:29.239 --> 00:15:33.239
just knew that primary and secondary were the names of those variables.

00:15:33.239 --> 00:15:36.239
So how do we know what variables to type in?

00:15:36.239 --> 00:15:39.239
So there are links here to the variable list.

00:15:39.239 --> 00:15:42.239
I'll have a link to these again at the end.

00:15:42.239 --> 00:15:46.239
So there are hundreds of variables, but they're very sensibly named and grouped in the boot

00:15:46.239 --> 00:15:47.239
trap source code.

00:15:47.280 --> 00:15:51.280
In addition, we've written our own custom documentation for you fine folks in the Shiny

00:15:51.280 --> 00:15:55.280
community that are more along the lines of things that you might need to do.

00:15:55.280 --> 00:15:58.280
And these docs will be evolving over time as well.

00:15:58.280 --> 00:15:59.280
Okay.

00:15:59.280 --> 00:16:00.280
Real quick.

00:16:00.280 --> 00:16:05.280
One other thing that we have done to try to make this easier for you is we've built a

00:16:05.280 --> 00:16:07.280
real-time previewing tool.

00:16:07.280 --> 00:16:15.280
So instead of calling run app from Shiny, we call run with themer.

00:16:15.320 --> 00:16:19.320
And this launches that exact same app, but with this additional UI on the right.

00:16:19.320 --> 00:16:24.320
So in this case, like, let's change the background color to something ridiculous.

00:16:24.320 --> 00:16:28.320
And within, you know, a second or so, it updates.

00:16:28.320 --> 00:16:36.320
So let's change this to something reasonable, like RStudio official light gray.

00:16:36.320 --> 00:16:37.320
Okay.

00:16:37.320 --> 00:16:44.320
And then why don't we go all the way and change the font to the RStudio font.

00:16:44.359 --> 00:16:45.359
Okay.

00:16:45.359 --> 00:16:46.359
So that's looking pretty good now.

00:16:46.359 --> 00:16:53.359
And what this tool does is it prints out the source code that you need to make this

00:16:53.359 --> 00:16:54.359
permanent to the console.

00:16:54.359 --> 00:16:57.359
So I'll just copy this line.

00:16:57.359 --> 00:16:59.359
Add it here.

00:16:59.359 --> 00:17:08.359
And the next time I run this app without run with themer, you can see that it is updated.

00:17:08.359 --> 00:17:10.359
Thank you, the one person who clapped.

00:17:10.400 --> 00:17:11.400
No, I wasn't.

00:17:11.400 --> 00:17:12.400
Okay.

00:17:12.400 --> 00:17:13.400
I'll take it.

00:17:13.400 --> 00:17:14.400
I'll take it.

00:17:14.400 --> 00:17:15.400
Yeah.

00:17:15.400 --> 00:17:16.400
Okay.

00:17:16.400 --> 00:17:17.400
Okay.

00:17:17.400 --> 00:17:18.400
So just one other thing.

00:17:18.400 --> 00:17:19.400
I'm not in a Steve Jobs fight.

00:17:19.400 --> 00:17:20.400
It's literally just one more thing.

00:17:20.400 --> 00:17:33.400
Now, one thing that's always bothered me personally about any time I try to punch up my Shiny apps,

00:17:33.400 --> 00:17:34.400
everybody likes dark mode, right?

00:17:34.400 --> 00:17:35.400
That's cool.

00:17:35.400 --> 00:17:36.400
But look at the background of this ggplot.

00:17:36.400 --> 00:17:37.400
It looks ridiculous.

00:17:37.400 --> 00:17:38.400
Right?

00:17:38.439 --> 00:17:44.439
The white around it just kind of throws off the whole effect.

00:17:44.439 --> 00:17:50.439
So what we've done with the next version of Shiny, hopefully, assuming Winston approves

00:17:50.439 --> 00:18:00.439
it, is a feature that you need to opt into called plot auto colors.

00:18:00.439 --> 00:18:05.439
It's so hard to type when hundreds of people are staring at you.

00:18:05.439 --> 00:18:06.439
Okay.

00:18:06.479 --> 00:18:10.479
So with that one line of code...

00:18:10.479 --> 00:18:15.479
All right.

00:18:15.479 --> 00:18:19.479
I showed my wife.

00:18:19.479 --> 00:18:23.479
She was not as impressed.

00:18:23.479 --> 00:18:29.479
With that one line of code, everywhere in your application you have a ggplot or a base

00:18:29.479 --> 00:18:35.479
plot or a lattice, we will try to apply some automatic defaults based on the colors in

00:18:35.520 --> 00:18:36.520
your DOM.

00:18:36.520 --> 00:18:40.520
And this is actually pretty sophisticated, and it has nothing to do with bootstrap.

00:18:40.520 --> 00:18:44.520
This is built into Shiny, not bootstrap lib.

00:18:44.520 --> 00:18:49.520
So you can take advantage of this feature when Shiny ships it with any kind of UI framework,

00:18:49.520 --> 00:18:53.520
including Shiny dashboard, flex dashboard, any of those others.

00:18:53.520 --> 00:18:54.520
Okay.

00:18:54.520 --> 00:18:56.520
So those are the instructions.

00:18:56.520 --> 00:19:01.520
Either you can set it application-wide with that Shiny option, or you can pass individual

00:19:01.560 --> 00:19:07.560
auto colors equals true to render plot if you want to opt in or out on a plot-by-plot

00:19:07.560 --> 00:19:08.560
basis.

00:19:08.560 --> 00:19:09.560
Okay.

00:19:09.560 --> 00:19:15.560
Before we get to questions, I just want to point out that third-party packages that want

00:19:15.560 --> 00:19:21.560
to take advantage of bootstrap and bootstrap lib coloring, they will have to be updated.

00:19:21.560 --> 00:19:25.560
So HTML widgets will need to be updated if they want to take advantage of this functionality.

00:19:25.560 --> 00:19:30.560
Our markdown document formats and Shiny extensions, like ShinyBS and Shiny widgets.

00:19:30.599 --> 00:19:34.599
The ones of these that RStudio maintains, we will take care of updating.

00:19:34.599 --> 00:19:40.599
And for the ones that are maintained by third-party package maintainers, if you're in this room,

00:19:40.599 --> 00:19:44.599
we would love to work with you, we would love to support you as we try to get people onto

00:19:44.599 --> 00:19:47.599
this infrastructure.

00:19:47.599 --> 00:19:54.599
I just want to acknowledge that bootstrap lib is built using both bootstrap 3 or bootstrap

00:19:54.599 --> 00:19:59.599
4, which is the first time that RStudio has taken the plunge into bootstrap 4.

00:19:59.640 --> 00:20:02.640
I'm not going to talk much more about this today unless people have specific questions,

00:20:02.640 --> 00:20:07.640
but I just want to point out that this is laying the groundwork towards moving everything

00:20:07.640 --> 00:20:11.640
to bootstrap 4, which is something that is going to happen over the course of the next

00:20:11.640 --> 00:20:12.640
year or so.

00:20:12.640 --> 00:20:16.640
Finally, I want to acknowledge, number one, some prior art.

00:20:16.640 --> 00:20:19.640
We didn't know about this package until we were pretty far along in the development,

00:20:19.640 --> 00:20:25.640
but there's a package from the DreamRs organization called Fresh that accomplishes many of the

00:20:25.680 --> 00:20:30.680
same goals, but without the sort of benefit of being the maintainers of Shiny.

00:20:30.680 --> 00:20:34.680
So I think they've done some really clever work that's very cool, and it works with a

00:20:34.680 --> 00:20:36.680
lot of packages already today.

00:20:36.680 --> 00:20:39.680
And I think because we were able to kind of change things from the inside, we were able

00:20:39.680 --> 00:20:43.680
to achieve a slightly different workflow that hopefully will build a better foundation for

00:20:43.680 --> 00:20:44.680
the future.

00:20:44.680 --> 00:20:47.680
But I just want to acknowledge that they've done some excellent work there.

00:20:47.680 --> 00:20:53.680
And then Sass was primarily implemented by Tim Masny, who was a summer intern, and bootstrap

00:20:53.719 --> 00:20:58.719
lib was mostly written by Carson Seabrook, who will be speaking next on Shinymeta.

00:20:58.719 --> 00:20:59.719
Thank you.

00:20:59.719 --> 00:21:00.719
Thanks, Joe.

00:21:00.719 --> 00:21:01.719
That's great.

00:21:01.719 --> 00:21:10.719
Thanks for applying public pressure on my ability to make a choice about this.

00:21:10.719 --> 00:21:11.719
All right.

00:21:11.719 --> 00:21:14.719
So let's get the questions here.

00:21:14.719 --> 00:21:15.719
All right.

00:21:15.719 --> 00:21:18.719
Why is bootstrap lib all written in Snakecase?

00:21:18.719 --> 00:21:20.719
All written in Snakecase?

00:21:20.719 --> 00:21:21.719
You know why.

00:21:21.760 --> 00:21:22.760
Yeah.

00:21:22.760 --> 00:21:23.760
Yeah.

00:21:23.760 --> 00:21:25.760
So why is it written in Snakecase?

00:21:25.760 --> 00:21:31.760
Shiny was written in CamelCase because in 2012, I think, I didn't have strong opinions

00:21:31.760 --> 00:21:35.760
and I was just kind of going by what I thought most people wanted.

00:21:35.760 --> 00:21:37.760
And I get that question a lot.

00:21:37.760 --> 00:21:39.760
Like, why aren't we moving everything to Snakecase?

00:21:39.760 --> 00:21:43.760
So it's very hard to move Shiny itself to Snakecase because of backwards compatibility.

00:21:43.760 --> 00:21:48.760
But where we have the opportunity to create brand new packages, you know, why not go with

00:21:48.800 --> 00:21:51.800
at least what it seems to me like the Shiny community is asking for,

00:21:51.800 --> 00:21:56.800
which is more not only Snakecase, but moving to sort of like input underscore select

00:21:56.800 --> 00:21:59.800
instead of select input.

00:21:59.800 --> 00:22:03.800
Do Plot Autocallers propagate to Plotly plots?

00:22:03.800 --> 00:22:04.800
No.

00:22:04.800 --> 00:22:05.800
Do Plot...

00:22:05.800 --> 00:22:07.800
There's no reason why they couldn't.

00:22:07.800 --> 00:22:12.800
But currently, we've been focused on the static side of things.

00:22:12.800 --> 00:22:13.800
Yeah.

00:22:13.800 --> 00:22:14.800
Is that right?

00:22:14.800 --> 00:22:15.800
Yeah.

00:22:15.800 --> 00:22:16.800
Okay.

00:22:16.800 --> 00:22:17.800
One more.

00:22:17.839 --> 00:22:19.839
When will Shiny move to Bootstrap 4?

00:22:22.839 --> 00:22:25.839
Yeah, that was going to be my entire talk today.

00:22:25.839 --> 00:22:29.839
And then it turned out that the theming stuff took all 20 minutes.

00:22:29.839 --> 00:22:32.839
It's going to be a process over this year, but we are intent on moving in a way

00:22:32.839 --> 00:22:35.839
that does not break backwards compatibility.

00:22:35.839 --> 00:22:40.839
So I think we've landed on a strategy that is going to let us very organically

00:22:40.839 --> 00:22:44.839
allow people to move to Bootstrap 4 without ever breaking the promises

00:22:44.839 --> 00:22:45.839
that we've made.

00:22:45.880 --> 00:22:47.880
So I think it's something that you should expect to see evolve

00:22:47.880 --> 00:22:49.880
over the next 12 to 24 months.

00:22:51.880 --> 00:22:52.880
Thank you.

00:22:52.880 --> 00:22:53.880
Thanks a lot, Joe.

